df <-read.csv("df.csv")

df = df[is.na(df$X2010.01.31) == FALSE,]
df = df[df$RegionName != "Summit County",]



df_value = df[,130:270]

df_value_copy = df_value

#df_value_copy$X2021.09.30/df_value_copy$X2010.01.31 - 1


for(i in 2:141){
  df_value[,i-1] = log(df_value[,i]/df_value[,i-1])
}
df_value = df_value[,-141]
total_growth = apply(df_value,1,sum)

aggregate_growth_df = data.frame( aggregate_growth = total_growth, County_name = df$RegionName, State_name = df$StateName)

aggregate_growth_df = aggregate_growth_df[order(aggregate_growth_df$aggregate_growth,decreasing = T),]

mean_state_growth_rate = aggregate_growth_df%>%group_by(State_name)%>%summarize(Growth_mean = mean(aggregate_growth))


mean_state_growth_rate = mean_state_growth_rate[order(mean_state_growth_rate$Growth_mean,decreasing = T),]

df_270 = df[,270]
twentytwenty_price = data.frame(price = df_270,county = df$RegionName, state = df$StateName)

mean_state_2020_price = twentytwenty_price%>%group_by(state)%>%summarize(mean_2020 = mean(price))
mean_state_2020_price = mean_state_2020_price[order(mean_state_2020_price$mean_2020,decreasing = T),]



df_130 = df[,130]
twentyten_price = data.frame(price = df_130,county = df$RegionName, state = df$StateName)


mean_state_2010_price = twentyten_price%>%group_by(state)%>%summarize(mean_2010 = mean(price))
mean_state_2010_price = mean_state_2010_price[order(mean_state_2010_price$mean_2010,decreasing = T),]
mean_state_2010_price$price_2010_rank = 1:nrow(mean_state_2010_price)



mean_state_2020_price$current_price_rank <- 1:nrow(mean_state_2020_price)
mean_state_growth_rate$growth_rank <- 1:nrow(mean_state_growth_rate)

ranking_df = merge(mean_state_2020_price,mean_state_growth_rate, by.x = "state",by.y = "State_name")


ranking_df = merge(ranking_df,mean_state_2010_price,by ="state" )



BLUE_states = c("CA","NV","OR","WA","NM","CO","MN","WI","MI","IL","PA","ME","NH","VT","NY","VA","MA","RI","CT","NJ","DE","MD","DC","HI")


PURPLE_states = c("FL","OH","IA")

RED_states = ranking_df$state %in% c(PURPLE_states,BLUE_states)

RED_states =  ranking_df$state[BLUE_states == FALSE]


for (i in 1: 50){if (ranking_df$state[i] %in% BLUE_states){
  ranking_df$state_color[i] = "Democrat"
}
else if(ranking_df$state[i] %in% PURPLE_states){
  ranking_df$state_color[i] = "Swing"
}
  else{
     ranking_df$state_color[i] = "Republican"
}
  }


ranking_df$color = "Other States"
ranking_df$color[as.numeric(rownames(ranking_df[which(abs(ranking_df$price_2010_rank - ranking_df$current_price_rank)<  0.25 * mean(abs(ranking_df$price_2010_rank - ranking_df$current_price_rank))),]
))
] = c(ranking_df[which(abs(ranking_df$price_2010_rank - ranking_df$current_price_rank)<  0.25 * mean(abs(ranking_df$price_2010_rank - ranking_df$current_price_rank))),]$state)

myplot <- ggplot(data=ranking_df,aes(x= price_2010_rank,y= current_price_rank,colour=color,shape = state_color))+ geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1)+geom_point() + scale_shape_manual(values = c(11,15, 17))  +   theme(legend.key.size = unit(0.1, 'cm')) + labs(title="Ranking of Average Housing Value by State 2010.1  vs  2021.9",
        x ="2010.1 Ranking", y = "2021.9 Ranking") + theme(
plot.title = element_text(color="black", size=10, face="bold.italic",hjust = 0.5),
axis.title.x = element_text(color="black", size=11, face="bold"),
axis.title.y = element_text(color="black", size=11, face="bold")
)

saved_df = ranking_df[,-c(8,9)]
colnames(saved_df) = c("State","2021 Mean Housing Value","2021 Ranking","Mean Growth Rate","Growth Ranking","2010 Mean Housing Value","2010 Ranking")

myplot

# With the county level housing values from 2010/1 data and 2021/9 data , for each of them, I grouped the data by states, and calculated the mean housing value for each state and ranked the 50 states by their mean housing values (Add the housing value of counties that belong to the same state and take the mean). I also found data on Wikipedia about the summary of results of the 2008, 2012, 2016, and 2020 presidential elections by state. I categorized the states into three categories. "Republican" for states that were carried by the Republicans in all four elections or in three of the four elections. Swing" for states that were carried by each party twice in the four elections. "Democrat" for states that were carried by the Democrats in three of the four elections or carried by the Democrats in all four elections. I made a scatter plot where x axis is the ranking of the states calculated with the housing values from 2010/1 data, and y axis is the ranking of the states calculated with the housing values from 2021/9 data. The black line is drawn with the expression y = x. If the rank of a state's mean housing value remains the same to other states from 2010 to 2021, we would expect to see the dot that represents the state lies on the black line. If the rank of a state's mean housing value remains similar to other states from 2010 to 2021, we would expect to see the dot that represents the state lies close to the black line. I calculated the average change of ranking of all 50 states from 2010/1 to 2021/9, and it is 4.431373. Among the 50 states on the scatter plot, I used special colors to color the states with a change in ranking that is less than a quarter of the average change of ranking, which is 1.107843 (4.431373 * 0.25). The states that did not fall under this criteria were all colored with violet and named "Other States". Besides coloring them differently, I also represent each state with different shapes in the scatter plot to show if they are "Republican", "Democrat" or "Swing" according to the results of the past four presidential elections.

# Some interesting findings,
# 1. 6 out of the top 10 highest ranked states in 2010.1 stayed in the top 10 in 2021.9. In 2010.1, 9 out of the top 10 states are Democrat. In 2021.9, 8 out of the top 10 states are Democrat.
# 2. The bottom 5 ranked states in 2010.1 stayed in the bottom 5 in 2021.9. The bottom 4 are Republican. 
# 3. More variation of rankings can be found in states that had a ranking between 7 to 21 and 33 to 46 in 2010.1, while the state that was ranked 30th (NV) in 2010.1 was an exception. NV had the highest mean growth rate among all 50 states (A total log return of 0.8780787) from 2010.1 to 2021.9 as you can see in the data frame below.
# 4. States that were ranked 22 to 32, (excluding 30th), in 2010,1 all dropped slightly in their ranking of 2021.9.
# 5. For states that had a ranking between 7 to 21, in 2021, the states that were ranked higher in 2010 tend to swap ranking with states that were ranked lower in 2010.
# 6. Same pattern can be found for states that were ranked between 33 to 46 in 2010

4.431373 * 0.25
## [1] 1.107843
data_points = c(1:140)


coefficients_list = numeric()

for (i in 1:2037){
  lm_model = lm(unname(unlist(df_value[i,,drop = T])) ~ data_points)
  coefficients_list = c(coefficients_list,lm_model$coefficients[2])
}

df$growth_rate = unname(coefficients_list)
top_20 = sort(coefficients_list, decreasing = T)[1:20]


desired_top20_df = df[df$growth_rate %in% top_20,]

desired_top20_df = desired_top20_df[order(-desired_top20_df$growth_rate),]





ggplot(data=desired_top20_df, aes(x = reorder(RegionName, growth_rate), y=growth_rate, fill = StateName)) + geom_bar(stat="identity", color="blue") + coord_flip() + labs(title = "Top 20 Regions in America with the Fastest Housing Value Growth Rate", y = "Growth Rate") + theme_grey(base_size = 7)
